<div class="headline_container  block_header in-block subheadline">
<div class="altblock"></div>
<div class="headline_info">
<div class="method_label">Section 1 of 6:</div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Correct-Tongue-Posture">Correct Tongue Posture</span></h3>
</div>
<a class="large_pdf_link pdf_link  disabled  pdf_link_steps  " href="#">
	
	<img class="pdf_link-img" loading="lazy" src="/extensions/wikihow/socialstamp/images/icon-pdf.svg" alt="PDF download" width="150" height="150">
	<span class="pdfText">Download Article</span>
	
</a>
</div>
<div id="steps_1" class="section_text">
<ol class="steps_list_2">
<li id="step-id-00">
<a name="step_1_1" class="stepanchor"></a><div class="mwimg  largeimage  floatcenter "><a href="#/Image:Tongue-Posture-Step-1-Version-2.jpg" class="image"><picture id="4caeb0e03cf1776066a9ea053ec603a2"><source type="image/webp" media="(max-width: 728px)" width="460" height="546" srcset="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/1c/Tongue-Posture-Step-1-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-1-Version-2.jpg.webp 460w"></source><source type="image/jpeg" media="(max-width: 728px)" width="460" height="546" srcset="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/1c/Tongue-Posture-Step-1-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-1-Version-2.jpg 460w"></source><source type="image/webp" media="(min-width: 729px)" width="728" height="546" srcset="/images/thumb/1/1c/Tongue-Posture-Step-1-Version-2.jpg/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-1-Version-2.jpg.webp 728w"></source><source type="image/jpeg" media="(min-width: 729px)" width="728" height="546" srcset="/images/thumb/1/1c/Tongue-Posture-Step-1-Version-2.jpg/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-1-Version-2.jpg 728w"></source><img alt="The tongue should rest along your palate with the tip behind your teeth." src="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/1c/Tongue-Posture-Step-1-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-1-Version-2.jpg" decoding="async" class="whcdn" width="460" height="345" priority="high" onload="WH.performance.clearMarks('image1_rendered'); WH.performance.mark('image1_rendered');"><script>WH.performance.clearMarks('image1_rendered'); WH.performance.mark('image1_rendered');</script></picture><div class="image_details"><script type="application/json">{"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/1\/1c\/Tongue-Posture-Step-1-Version-2.jpg\/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-1-Version-2.jpg","bigUrl":"\/images\/thumb\/1\/1c\/Tongue-Posture-Step-1-Version-2.jpg\/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-1-Version-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":728,"bigHeight":546,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>\u00a9 2025 wikiHow, Inc. All rights reserved. wikiHow, Inc. is the copyright holder of this image under U.S. and international copyright laws. This image may not be used by other entities without the express written consent of wikiHow, Inc.<br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}</script></div></a></div><div class="step">
<b class="whb" aria-hidden="true">The tongue should rest along your palate with the tip behind your teeth.</b> At rest (when you’re not talking or eating), the tip of your tongue should sit on the roof of your mouth just behind your top front teeth, near where your gums and teeth meet or slightly behind. The rest of your tongue should be slightly arched and relaxed along the roof of your mouth (your hard palate).<sup id="_ref-1" class="reference" aria-label="Link to Reference 1"><a href="#_note-1">[1]</a><span class="ts_popup " hidden id="ts_popup_1" style="display: none;">
	<span class="ts_close">X</span>
		<span class="ts_name">Research source</span>
		<span class="ts_description"></span>
				<a href="#" class="ts_source" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"></a>

</span>
</sup> Your lips will also be closed, your top and bottom teeth will be slightly separated or just barely touching, and nose breathing should feel easy and natural.<sup id="_ref-2" class="reference" aria-label="Link to Reference 2"><a href="#_note-2">[2]</a><span class="ts_popup " hidden id="ts_popup_2" style="display: none;">
	<span class="ts_close">X</span>
		<span class="ts_name">Research source</span>
		<span class="ts_description"></span>
				<a href="#" class="ts_source" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"></a>

</span>
</sup>
<ul>
<li>
<b>When swallowing,</b> the front of the tongue should be held against the roof of the mouth while the back of the tongue contracts to push food down your esophagus.<sup id="_ref-3" class="reference" aria-label="Link to Reference 3"><a href="#_note-3">[3]</a><span class="ts_popup " hidden id="ts_popup_3" style="display: none;">
	<span class="ts_close">X</span>
		<span class="ts_name">Research source</span>
		<span class="ts_description"></span>
				<a href="#" class="ts_source" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"></a>

</span>
</sup>
</li>
<li>
<b>When speaking,</b> your tongue will move into all sorts of shapes or positions depending on the sounds (especially vowel sounds) you’re making. For example, “ah” or “uh” syllables cause the tongue to drop lower, while “ee” or “ay” syllables make it go higher.<sup id="_ref-4" class="reference" aria-label="Link to Reference 4"><a href="#_note-4">[4]</a><span class="ts_popup " hidden id="ts_popup_4" style="display: none;">
	<span class="ts_close">X</span>
		<span class="ts_name">Research source</span>
		<span class="ts_description"></span>
				<a href="#" class="ts_source" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"></a>

</span>
</sup>
</li>
<li>After swallowing or speaking, your tongue should return to its neutral, resting posture.</li>
</ul>
<script>WH.performance.mark('step1_rendered');</script>
</div>
<div class="clearall"></div>
<div class="scrolltomarker" data-isstep="1" id="scrollto_marker_steps_1"></div>
</li>
<div class="wh_ad_inner w_label al_grey dfpsmall dfpsmallmethod containerless_ad fluid" data-service="adsense" data-slot="7710650179" data-width="728" data-height="90" data-smallheight="250" data-type="method" data-small="1" data-channels="4657739586" data-smallservice="dfp" data-adunitpath="/10095428/engl/engl_gam_sma_meth0" data-size='[[300, 250],"fluid"]' data-apsload="1" data-prebidload="1" data-aps-timeout="800" data-containerless="1" data-fullwidthadsense="1" data-fluidsize="1" data-mediumchannels="3005955957,4066873649" data-smallchannels="2811805837,8156154280" data-aditudetarget="pb-slot-engl-meth" data-largechannels="2060152247,5763098696" data-insertslotvalue="1" data-pagetype="methods" data-observerloading="1" data-sizes-array='[[300, 250],"fluid"]' data-gptdisplaylate="1" data-pbadunits='{"appnexus":29111279,"pubmatic":"4926794","ix":"944751","amx":"d2lraWhvdy5jb20","rubicon":"2756126","shemedia":"2952570","openx":"558892622","triplelift":"Wikihow_engl_gam_sma_meth0_300x250_Prebid","yieldmo":"3204666393567896410","grid":383057,"medianet":"521047606","rise":"engl_gam_sma_meth0","sharethrough":"xZq2HSiUJL1GRBHUi49ybeLd"}'><div id="mobilemethod_ad_1"></div></div>
<div class="al_method">Advertisement</div>
<script>WH.ads.addBodyAd('mobilemethod_ad_1')</script>
</ol>
<div class="clearall"></div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="section steps   sticky hide_step_numbers font_test">
<div class="headline_container  block_header in-block subheadline">
<div class="altblock"></div>
<div class="headline_info">
<div class="method_label">Section 2 of 6:</div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Identifying-Poor-Tongue-Posture">Identifying Poor Tongue Posture
</span></h3>
</div>
<a class="large_pdf_link pdf_link  disabled  pdf_link_steps  " href="#">
	
	<img class="pdf_link-img" loading="lazy" src="/extensions/wikihow/socialstamp/images/icon-pdf.svg" alt="PDF download" width="150" height="150">
	<span class="pdfText">Download Article</span>
	
</a>
</div>
<div id="steps_2" class="section_text">
<ol class="steps_list_2">
<li id="step-id-11">
<a name="step_2_1" class="stepanchor"></a><div class="mwimg  largeimage  floatcenter "><a href="#/Image:Tongue-Posture-Step-2-Version-2.jpg" class="image"><picture id="124909beba5145b0e4948af137ede45e"><source type="image/webp" media="(max-width: 728px)" width="460" height="546" srcset="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/79/Tongue-Posture-Step-2-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-2-Version-2.jpg.webp 460w"></source><source type="image/jpeg" media="(max-width: 728px)" width="460" height="546" srcset="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/79/Tongue-Posture-Step-2-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-2-Version-2.jpg 460w"></source><source type="image/webp" media="(min-width: 729px)" width="728" height="546" srcset="/images/thumb/7/79/Tongue-Posture-Step-2-Version-2.jpg/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-2-Version-2.jpg.webp 728w"></source><source type="image/jpeg" media="(min-width: 729px)" width="728" height="546" srcset="/images/thumb/7/79/Tongue-Posture-Step-2-Version-2.jpg/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-2-Version-2.jpg 728w"></source><img alt="Step 1 Does your tongue push forward into your teeth?" src="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/79/Tongue-Posture-Step-2-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-2-Version-2.jpg" decoding="async" class="whcdn" width="460" height="345" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image_details"><script type="application/json">{"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/7\/79\/Tongue-Posture-Step-2-Version-2.jpg\/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-2-Version-2.jpg","bigUrl":"\/images\/thumb\/7\/79\/Tongue-Posture-Step-2-Version-2.jpg\/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-2-Version-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":728,"bigHeight":546,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>\u00a9 2025 wikiHow, Inc. All rights reserved. wikiHow, Inc. is the copyright holder of this image under U.S. and international copyright laws. This image may not be used by other entities without the express written consent of wikiHow, Inc.<br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}</script></div></a></div>
<div class="step_num" aria-hidden="true">1</div><div class="step">
<b class="whb" aria-hidden="true">Does your tongue push forward into your teeth?</b> This condition is called “tongue thrust” and is a common tongue position problem in children that can continue into adulthood if left untreated. The most obvious sign of tongue thrust is the tongue sticking out of the mouth slightly when swallowing or speaking certain syllables. Other symptoms include:<sup id="_ref-5" class="reference trusted" aria-label="Link to Reference 5"><a href="#_note-5">[5]</a><span class="ts_popup trustedsource" hidden id="ts_popup_5" style="display: none;">
	<span class="ts_close">X</span>
		<a class="ts_trustworthy" href="/wikiHow:Delivering-a-Trustworthy-Experience">Trustworthy Source</a>

		<span class="ts_name">Cleveland Clinic</span>
		<span class="ts_description">Educational website from one of the world's leading hospitals</span>

				<a href="#" class="ts_source" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Go to source</a>
</span>
</sup>
<ul>
<li>Trouble swallowing</li>
<li>Problems with food falling out of the mouth</li>
<li>Accidentally biting the tongue or cheeks</li>
<li>Mouth breathing</li>
<li>Trouble pronouncing sounds like “S,” “Z,” “Sh,” and “J”</li>
<li>
<b>What causes tongue thrust?</b> Tongue thrust commonly occurs when infants don’t outgrow their “tongue thrust reflex” from nursing. It may also be caused by using pacifiers past age 3, conditions like allergies that cause mouth breathing, nervous system conditions, or anxiety.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div class="clearall"></div>
<div class="scrolltomarker" data-isstep="1" id="scrollto_marker_steps_2"></div>
</li>
<li id="step-id-12">
<a name="step_2_2" class="stepanchor"></a><div class="mwimg  largeimage  floatcenter "><a href="#/Image:Tongue-Posture-Step-3-Version-2.jpg" class="image"><picture id="4116369669165f630d5f693bf58d3aa1"><source type="image/webp" media="(max-width: 728px)" width="460" height="546" srcset="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2f/Tongue-Posture-Step-3-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-3-Version-2.jpg.webp 460w"></source><source type="image/jpeg" media="(max-width: 728px)" width="460" height="546" srcset="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2f/Tongue-Posture-Step-3-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-3-Version-2.jpg 460w"></source><source type="image/webp" media="(min-width: 729px)" width="728" height="546" srcset="/images/thumb/2/2f/Tongue-Posture-Step-3-Version-2.jpg/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-3-Version-2.jpg.webp 728w"></source><source type="image/jpeg" media="(min-width: 729px)" width="728" height="546" srcset="/images/thumb/2/2f/Tongue-Posture-Step-3-Version-2.jpg/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-3-Version-2.jpg 728w"></source><img alt="Step 2 Does your tongue lay too low in your mouth?" src="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2f/Tongue-Posture-Step-3-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-3-Version-2.jpg" decoding="async" class="whcdn" width="460" height="345" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image_details"><script type="application/json">{"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/2\/2f\/Tongue-Posture-Step-3-Version-2.jpg\/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-3-Version-2.jpg","bigUrl":"\/images\/thumb\/2\/2f\/Tongue-Posture-Step-3-Version-2.jpg\/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-3-Version-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":728,"bigHeight":546,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>\u00a9 2025 wikiHow, Inc. All rights reserved. wikiHow, Inc. is the copyright holder of this image under U.S. and international copyright laws. This image may not be used by other entities without the express written consent of wikiHow, Inc.<br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}</script></div></a></div>
<div class="step_num" aria-hidden="true">2</div><div class="step">
<b class="whb" aria-hidden="true">Does your tongue lay too low in your mouth?</b> This is called a low tongue rest position (LTRP) and happens when the tongue habitually doesn’t make contact with the hard palate due to nasal breathing problems.<sup id="_ref-6" class="reference" aria-label="Link to Reference 6"><a href="#_note-6">[6]</a><span class="ts_popup " hidden id="ts_popup_6" style="display: none;">
	<span class="ts_close">X</span>
		<span class="ts_name">Research source</span>
		<span class="ts_description"></span>
				<a href="#" class="ts_source" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"></a>

</span>
</sup> Try moving your tongue high up into the roof of your mouth, then lowering it into the floor of your mouth—you’ll feel a noticeable change in your jaw and throat. If the low position feels more normal, you may have poor tongue posture.<sup id="_ref-7" class="reference" aria-label="Link to Reference 7"><a href="#_note-7">[7]</a><span class="ts_popup " hidden id="ts_popup_7" style="display: none;">
	<span class="ts_close">X</span>
		<span class="ts_name">Research source</span>
		<span class="ts_description"></span>
				<a href="#" class="ts_source" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"></a>

</span>
</sup> Other signs of LTRP include:
<ul>
<li>Neck or jaw pain</li>
<li>A jaw that protrudes slightly forward and/or hangs low</li>
<li>Drooling and/or snoring</li>
<li>Difficulty reaching the roof of the mouth with the tongue</li>
<li>Mouth breathing or the inability to close the lips fully<sup id="_ref-8" class="reference" aria-label="Link to Reference 8"><a href="#_note-8">[8]</a><span class="ts_popup " hidden id="ts_popup_8" style="display: none;">
	<span class="ts_close">X</span>
		<span class="ts_name">Research source</span>
		<span class="ts_description"></span>
				<a href="#" class="ts_source" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"></a>

</span>
</sup>
</li>
<li>Tongue pressing against the back of the lower teeth (tongue thrust)</li>
<li>If the tongue is low and also off-center (pointing any direction but straight forward), the jaw may also become misaligned.</li>
<li>
<b>What causes low tongue rest position?</b> Chronic interruptions to nasal breathing (like allergies or a medical condition) cause the jaw and tongue to drop and go forward to open up your airways. Over time, this low position can become a habit (even once nasal breathing improves).<sup id="_ref-9" class="reference" aria-label="Link to Reference 9"><a href="#_note-9">[9]</a><span class="ts_popup " hidden id="ts_popup_9" style="display: none;">
	<span class="ts_close">X</span>
		<span class="ts_name">Research source</span>
		<span class="ts_description"></span>
				<a href="#" class="ts_source" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"></a>

</span>
</sup>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div class="clearall"></div>
<div class="scrolltomarker" data-isstep="1" id="scrollto_marker_steps_3"></div>
</li>
<div class="wh_ad_inner w_label al_grey dfpsmall dfpsmallmethod containerless_ad fluid" data-service="adsense" data-slot="7710650179" data-width="728" data-height="90" data-smallheight="250" data-type="method" data-small="1" data-channels="4657739586" data-smallservice="dfp" data-adunitpath="/10095428/engl/engl_gam_sma_meth0" data-size='[[300, 250],"fluid"]' data-apsload="1" data-prebidload="1" data-aps-timeout="800" data-containerless="1" data-fullwidthadsense="1" data-fluidsize="1" data-mediumchannels="3005955957,4066873649" data-smallchannels="2811805837,8156154280" data-aditudetarget="pb-slot-engl-meth" data-largechannels="2060152247,5763098696" data-insertslotvalue="2" data-pagetype="methods" data-observerloading="1" data-sizes-array='[[300, 250],"fluid"]' data-gptdisplaylate="1" data-pbadunits='{"appnexus":29111279,"pubmatic":"4926794","ix":"944751","amx":"d2lraWhvdy5jb20","rubicon":"2756126","shemedia":"2952570","openx":"558892622","triplelift":"Wikihow_engl_gam_sma_meth0_300x250_Prebid","yieldmo":"3204666393567896410","grid":383057,"medianet":"521047606","rise":"engl_gam_sma_meth0","sharethrough":"xZq2HSiUJL1GRBHUi49ybeLd"}'><div id="mobilemethod_ad_2"></div></div>
<div class="al_method">Advertisement</div>
<script>WH.ads.addBodyAd('mobilemethod_ad_2')</script>
</ol>
<div class="clearall"></div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="section steps   sticky hide_step_numbers font_test">
<div class="headline_container  block_header in-block subheadline">
<div class="altblock"></div>
<div class="headline_info">
<div class="method_label">Section 3 of 6:</div>
<span id="Why-is-good-tongue-posture-important?"></span><h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Why-is-good-tongue-posture-important.3F">Why is good tongue posture important?
</span></h3>
</div>
<a class="large_pdf_link pdf_link  disabled  pdf_link_steps  " href="#">
	
	<img class="pdf_link-img" loading="lazy" src="/extensions/wikihow/socialstamp/images/icon-pdf.svg" alt="PDF download" width="150" height="150">
	<span class="pdfText">Download Article</span>
	
</a>
</div>
<div id="steps_3" class="section_text">
<ol class="steps_list_2"><li id="step-id-23">
<a name="step_3_1" class="stepanchor"></a><div class="mwimg  largeimage  floatcenter "><a href="#/Image:Tongue-Posture-Step-4-Version-2.jpg" class="image"><picture id="4fad6d88b19e82a83ebc16a1027e21be"><source type="image/webp" media="(max-width: 728px)" width="460" height="546" srcset="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/fc/Tongue-Posture-Step-4-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-4-Version-2.jpg.webp 460w"></source><source type="image/jpeg" media="(max-width: 728px)" width="460" height="546" srcset="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/fc/Tongue-Posture-Step-4-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-4-Version-2.jpg 460w"></source><source type="image/webp" media="(min-width: 729px)" width="728" height="546" srcset="/images/thumb/f/fc/Tongue-Posture-Step-4-Version-2.jpg/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-4-Version-2.jpg.webp 728w"></source><source type="image/jpeg" media="(min-width: 729px)" width="728" height="546" srcset="/images/thumb/f/fc/Tongue-Posture-Step-4-Version-2.jpg/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-4-Version-2.jpg 728w"></source><img alt="Proper tongue posture supports correct oral development." src="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/fc/Tongue-Posture-Step-4-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-4-Version-2.jpg" decoding="async" class="whcdn" width="460" height="345" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image_details"><script type="application/json">{"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/f\/fc\/Tongue-Posture-Step-4-Version-2.jpg\/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-4-Version-2.jpg","bigUrl":"\/images\/thumb\/f\/fc\/Tongue-Posture-Step-4-Version-2.jpg\/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-4-Version-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":728,"bigHeight":546,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>\u00a9 2025 wikiHow, Inc. All rights reserved. wikiHow, Inc. is the copyright holder of this image under U.S. and international copyright laws. This image may not be used by other entities without the express written consent of wikiHow, Inc.<br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}</script></div></a></div><div class="step">
<b class="whb" aria-hidden="true">Proper tongue posture supports correct oral development.</b> The tongue is a strong muscle that can exert force on your jaw, maxilla (upper jaw), and teeth. When it’s in the correct position, it uses this force to positively support your oral development and overall health. This includes benefits like:<sup id="_ref-10" class="reference" aria-label="Link to Reference 10"><a href="#_note-10">[10]</a><span class="ts_popup " hidden id="ts_popup_10" style="display: none;">
	<span class="ts_close">X</span>
		<span class="ts_name">Research source</span>
		<span class="ts_description"></span>
				<a href="#" class="ts_source" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"></a>

</span>
</sup>
<ul>
<li>Maintaining straighter teeth alignment</li>
<li>Preventing teeth grinding</li>
<li>Keeping your tongue from flopping backward</li>
<li>Preventing snoring and sleep apnea</li>
<li>Preventing mouth breathing</li>
<li>Expanding your palate to support your jaw and cheekbones as you age</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div class="clearall"></div>
<div class="scrolltomarker" data-isstep="1" id="scrollto_marker_steps_4"></div>
</li></ol>
<div class="clearall"></div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="section steps   sticky hide_step_numbers font_test">
<div class="headline_container  block_header in-block subheadline">
<div class="altblock"></div>
<div class="headline_info">
<div class="method_label">Section 4 of 6:</div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Side-Effects-of-Poor-Tongue-Posture">Side Effects of Poor Tongue Posture
</span></h3>
</div>
<a class="large_pdf_link pdf_link  disabled  pdf_link_steps  " href="#">
	
	<img class="pdf_link-img" loading="lazy" src="/extensions/wikihow/socialstamp/images/icon-pdf.svg" alt="PDF download" width="150" height="150">
	<span class="pdfText">Download Article</span>
	
</a>
</div>
<div id="steps_4" class="section_text">
<ol class="steps_list_2">
<li id="step-id-34">
<a name="step_4_1" class="stepanchor"></a><div class="mwimg  largeimage  floatcenter "><a href="#/Image:Tongue-Posture-Step-5-Version-2.jpg" class="image"><picture id="9d67b1d2edf334ed07bdad7b7a522528"><source type="image/webp" media="(max-width: 728px)" width="460" height="546" srcset="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/fb/Tongue-Posture-Step-5-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-5-Version-2.jpg.webp 460w"></source><source type="image/jpeg" media="(max-width: 728px)" width="460" height="546" srcset="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/fb/Tongue-Posture-Step-5-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-5-Version-2.jpg 460w"></source><source type="image/webp" media="(min-width: 729px)" width="728" height="546" srcset="/images/thumb/f/fb/Tongue-Posture-Step-5-Version-2.jpg/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-5-Version-2.jpg.webp 728w"></source><source type="image/jpeg" media="(min-width: 729px)" width="728" height="546" srcset="/images/thumb/f/fb/Tongue-Posture-Step-5-Version-2.jpg/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-5-Version-2.jpg 728w"></source><img alt="Step 1 Poor tongue posture can cause dental, facial, and muscular problems." src="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/fb/Tongue-Posture-Step-5-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-5-Version-2.jpg" decoding="async" class="whcdn" width="460" height="345" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image_details"><script type="application/json">{"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/f\/fb\/Tongue-Posture-Step-5-Version-2.jpg\/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-5-Version-2.jpg","bigUrl":"\/images\/thumb\/f\/fb\/Tongue-Posture-Step-5-Version-2.jpg\/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-5-Version-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":728,"bigHeight":546,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>\u00a9 2025 wikiHow, Inc. All rights reserved. wikiHow, Inc. is the copyright holder of this image under U.S. and international copyright laws. This image may not be used by other entities without the express written consent of wikiHow, Inc.<br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}</script></div></a></div>
<div class="step_num" aria-hidden="true">1</div><div class="step">
<b class="whb" aria-hidden="true">Poor tongue posture can cause dental, facial, and muscular problems.</b> Your tongue is a long, strong muscle whose position and movement can influence the development of other parts of your body like your mouth, head, neck, nose, eyes, and shoulders.<sup id="_ref-11" class="reference" aria-label="Link to Reference 11"><a href="#_note-11">[11]</a><span class="ts_popup " hidden id="ts_popup_11" style="display: none;">
	<span class="ts_close">X</span>
		<span class="ts_name">Research source</span>
		<span class="ts_description"></span>
				<a href="#" class="ts_source" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"></a>

</span>
</sup> Here’s what you may experience if severely poor tongue posture is left untreated long term:
<ul>
<li>
<b>Those with tongue thrust</b> may develop misaligned teeth, an underbite or overbite, gaps between the front two teeth, and/or jaw pain.<sup id="_ref-12" class="reference trusted" aria-label="Link to Reference 12"><a href="#_note-12">[12]</a><span class="ts_popup trustedsource" hidden id="ts_popup_12" style="display: none;">
	<span class="ts_close">X</span>
		<a class="ts_trustworthy" href="/wikiHow:Delivering-a-Trustworthy-Experience">Trustworthy Source</a>

		<span class="ts_name">Cleveland Clinic</span>
		<span class="ts_description">Educational website from one of the world's leading hospitals</span>

				<a href="#" class="ts_source" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Go to source</a>
</span>
</sup>
</li>
<li>
<b>Those with low tongue rest position</b> may develop a slightly longer, flatter face shape or a jaw/chin that protrudes forward (sometimes permanently).<sup id="_ref-13" class="reference" aria-label="Link to Reference 13"><a href="#_note-13">[13]</a><span class="ts_popup " hidden id="ts_popup_13" style="display: none;">
	<span class="ts_close">X</span>
		<span class="ts_name">Research source</span>
		<span class="ts_description"></span>
				<a href="#" class="ts_source" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"></a>

</span>
</sup>
</li>
<li>
<b>More long term complications</b> include poor body posture, vision problems, tooth damage, or conditions like sleep apnea, tooth grinding, or TMJ disorder.<sup id="_ref-14" class="reference" aria-label="Link to Reference 14"><a href="#_note-14">[14]</a><span class="ts_popup " hidden id="ts_popup_14" style="display: none;">
	<span class="ts_close">X</span>
		<span class="ts_name">Research source</span>
		<span class="ts_description"></span>
				<a href="#" class="ts_source" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"></a>

</span>
</sup>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div class="clearall"></div>
<div class="scrolltomarker" data-isstep="1" id="scrollto_marker_steps_5"></div>
</li>
<li id="step-id-35">
<a name="step_4_2" class="stepanchor"></a><div class="mwimg  largeimage  floatcenter "><a href="#/Image:Tongue-Posture-Step-6-Version-2.jpg" class="image"><picture id="44ddf6f77b763c69eaa2a80b35bc881d"><source type="image/webp" media="(max-width: 728px)" width="460" height="546" srcset="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7f/Tongue-Posture-Step-6-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-6-Version-2.jpg.webp 460w"></source><source type="image/jpeg" media="(max-width: 728px)" width="460" height="546" srcset="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7f/Tongue-Posture-Step-6-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-6-Version-2.jpg 460w"></source><source type="image/webp" media="(min-width: 729px)" width="728" height="546" srcset="/images/thumb/7/7f/Tongue-Posture-Step-6-Version-2.jpg/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-6-Version-2.jpg.webp 728w"></source><source type="image/jpeg" media="(min-width: 729px)" width="728" height="546" srcset="/images/thumb/7/7f/Tongue-Posture-Step-6-Version-2.jpg/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-6-Version-2.jpg 728w"></source><img alt="Step 2 Poor tongue posture may narrow your palate, jaw, cheekbones." src="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7f/Tongue-Posture-Step-6-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-6-Version-2.jpg" decoding="async" class="whcdn" width="460" height="345" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image_details"><script type="application/json">{"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/7\/7f\/Tongue-Posture-Step-6-Version-2.jpg\/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-6-Version-2.jpg","bigUrl":"\/images\/thumb\/7\/7f\/Tongue-Posture-Step-6-Version-2.jpg\/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-6-Version-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":728,"bigHeight":546,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>\u00a9 2025 wikiHow, Inc. All rights reserved. wikiHow, Inc. is the copyright holder of this image under U.S. and international copyright laws. This image may not be used by other entities without the express written consent of wikiHow, Inc.<br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}</script></div></a></div>
<div class="step_num" aria-hidden="true">2</div><div class="step">
<b class="whb" aria-hidden="true">Poor tongue posture may narrow your palate, jaw, cheekbones.</b> When the tongue rests properly against the roof of the mouth, it helps to expand your palate.<sup id="_ref-15" class="reference" aria-label="Link to Reference 15"><a href="#_note-15">[15]</a><span class="ts_popup " hidden id="ts_popup_15" style="display: none;">
	<span class="ts_close">X</span>
		<span class="ts_name">Research source</span>
		<span class="ts_description"></span>
				<a href="#" class="ts_source" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"></a>

</span>
</sup> This helps support your jaw and cheekbones, making them look slightly more pronounced. However, when the tongue is in the wrong place (especially when it’s too low), your palate can narrow, leading to a recessed jaw (and potentially less defined cheekbones).<sup id="_ref-16" class="reference" aria-label="Link to Reference 16"><a href="#_note-16">[16]</a><span class="ts_popup " hidden id="ts_popup_16" style="display: none;">
	<span class="ts_close">X</span>
		<span class="ts_name">Research source</span>
		<span class="ts_description"></span>
				<a href="#" class="ts_source" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"></a>

</span>
</sup>
<ul>
<li>Maintaining good tongue positioning can prevent the narrowing of your palate, jaw, or cheekbones. However, there’s no evidence yet that retraining your tongue to rest properly can <i>reverse</i> these effects once they’ve happened.</li>
<li>Some claim that <a href="/Mew" title="Mew">mewing</a> can widen the palate, but there is no evidence supporting this.<sup id="_ref-17" class="reference" aria-label="Link to Reference 17"><a href="#_note-17">[17]</a><span class="ts_popup " hidden id="ts_popup_17" style="display: none;">
	<span class="ts_close">X</span>
		<span class="ts_name">Research source</span>
		<span class="ts_description"></span>
				<a href="#" class="ts_source" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"></a>

</span>
</sup>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div class="clearall"></div>
<div class="scrolltomarker" data-isstep="1" id="scrollto_marker_steps_6"></div>
</li>
<li id="step-id-36">
<a name="step_4_3" class="stepanchor"></a><div class="mwimg  largeimage  floatcenter "><a href="#/Image:Tongue-Posture-Step-7-Version-2.jpg" class="image"><picture id="a894e0d482062223567540bcab96b8e6"><source type="image/webp" media="(max-width: 728px)" width="460" height="546" srcset="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5e/Tongue-Posture-Step-7-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-7-Version-2.jpg.webp 460w"></source><source type="image/jpeg" media="(max-width: 728px)" width="460" height="546" srcset="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5e/Tongue-Posture-Step-7-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-7-Version-2.jpg 460w"></source><source type="image/webp" media="(min-width: 729px)" width="728" height="546" srcset="/images/thumb/5/5e/Tongue-Posture-Step-7-Version-2.jpg/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-7-Version-2.jpg.webp 728w"></source><source type="image/jpeg" media="(min-width: 729px)" width="728" height="546" srcset="/images/thumb/5/5e/Tongue-Posture-Step-7-Version-2.jpg/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-7-Version-2.jpg 728w"></source><img alt="Step 3 Mouth breathing caused by tongue posture can also affect your health." src="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5e/Tongue-Posture-Step-7-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-7-Version-2.jpg" decoding="async" class="whcdn" width="460" height="345" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image_details"><script type="application/json">{"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/5\/5e\/Tongue-Posture-Step-7-Version-2.jpg\/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-7-Version-2.jpg","bigUrl":"\/images\/thumb\/5\/5e\/Tongue-Posture-Step-7-Version-2.jpg\/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-7-Version-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":728,"bigHeight":546,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>\u00a9 2025 wikiHow, Inc. All rights reserved. wikiHow, Inc. is the copyright holder of this image under U.S. and international copyright laws. This image may not be used by other entities without the express written consent of wikiHow, Inc.<br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}</script></div></a></div>
<div class="step_num" aria-hidden="true">3</div><div class="step">
<b class="whb" aria-hidden="true">Mouth breathing caused by tongue posture can also affect your health.</b> Although it sounds fairly innocent, long term mouth breathing as a result of a misplaced tongue can negatively impact your oral health, sleep, and other aspects of your health. The main risks include:<sup id="_ref-18" class="reference trusted" aria-label="Link to Reference 18"><a href="#_note-18">[18]</a><span class="ts_popup trustedsource" hidden id="ts_popup_18" style="display: none;">
	<span class="ts_close">X</span>
		<a class="ts_trustworthy" href="/wikiHow:Delivering-a-Trustworthy-Experience">Trustworthy Source</a>

		<span class="ts_name">Cleveland Clinic</span>
		<span class="ts_description">Educational website from one of the world's leading hospitals</span>

				<a href="#" class="ts_source" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Go to source</a>
</span>
</sup>
<ul>
<li>Sleep apnea or obstructive sleep apnea</li>
<li>Malocclusion (when the upper and lower teeth don’t align)</li>
<li>Dry mouth</li>
<li>Bad breath or halitosis</li>
<li>Drooling while sleeping or laying down</li>
<li>“Mouth breathing face” (a narrowed face with a receding chin or jaw)</li>
<li>Potential behavioral problems in children resembling ADHD symptoms</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div class="clearall"></div>
<div class="scrolltomarker" data-isstep="1" id="scrollto_marker_steps_7"></div>
</li>
<div class="wh_ad_inner w_label al_grey dfpsmall dfpsmallmethod containerless_ad fluid" data-service="adsense" data-slot="7710650179" data-width="728" data-height="90" data-smallheight="250" data-type="method" data-small="1" data-channels="4657739586" data-smallservice="dfp" data-adunitpath="/10095428/engl/engl_gam_sma_meth0" data-size='[[300, 250],"fluid"]' data-apsload="1" data-prebidload="1" data-aps-timeout="800" data-containerless="1" data-fullwidthadsense="1" data-fluidsize="1" data-mediumchannels="3005955957,4066873649" data-smallchannels="2811805837,8156154280" data-aditudetarget="pb-slot-engl-meth" data-largechannels="2060152247,5763098696" data-insertslotvalue="3" data-pagetype="methods" data-observerloading="1" data-sizes-array='[[300, 250],"fluid"]' data-gptdisplaylate="1" data-pbadunits='{"appnexus":29111279,"pubmatic":"4926794","ix":"944751","amx":"d2lraWhvdy5jb20","rubicon":"2756126","shemedia":"2952570","openx":"558892622","triplelift":"Wikihow_engl_gam_sma_meth0_300x250_Prebid","yieldmo":"3204666393567896410","grid":383057,"medianet":"521047606","rise":"engl_gam_sma_meth0","sharethrough":"xZq2HSiUJL1GRBHUi49ybeLd"}'><div id="mobilemethod_ad_4"></div></div>
<div class="al_method">Advertisement</div>
<script>WH.ads.addBodyAd('mobilemethod_ad_4')</script>
</ol>
<div class="clearall"></div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="section steps   sticky hide_step_numbers font_test">
<div class="headline_container  block_header in-block subheadline">
<div class="altblock"></div>
<div class="headline_info">
<div class="method_label">Section 5 of 6:</div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Correcting-Your-Tongue-Posture">Correcting Your Tongue Posture
</span></h3>
</div>
<a class="large_pdf_link pdf_link  disabled  pdf_link_steps  " href="#">
	
	<img class="pdf_link-img" loading="lazy" src="/extensions/wikihow/socialstamp/images/icon-pdf.svg" alt="PDF download" width="150" height="150">
	<span class="pdfText">Download Article</span>
	
</a>
</div>
<div id="steps_5" class="section_text">
<ol class="steps_list_2">
<li id="step-id-47">
<a name="step_5_1" class="stepanchor"></a><div class="mwimg  largeimage  floatcenter "><a href="#/Image:Tongue-Posture-Step-8-Version-2.jpg" class="image"><picture id="f3c6922ae6140c4e940b9b6c563cabe9"><source type="image/webp" media="(max-width: 728px)" width="460" height="546" srcset="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a4/Tongue-Posture-Step-8-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-8-Version-2.jpg.webp 460w"></source><source type="image/jpeg" media="(max-width: 728px)" width="460" height="546" srcset="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a4/Tongue-Posture-Step-8-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-8-Version-2.jpg 460w"></source><source type="image/webp" media="(min-width: 729px)" width="728" height="546" srcset="/images/thumb/a/a4/Tongue-Posture-Step-8-Version-2.jpg/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-8-Version-2.jpg.webp 728w"></source><source type="image/jpeg" media="(min-width: 729px)" width="728" height="546" srcset="/images/thumb/a/a4/Tongue-Posture-Step-8-Version-2.jpg/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-8-Version-2.jpg 728w"></source><img alt="Step 1 Tongue position awareness" src="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a4/Tongue-Posture-Step-8-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-8-Version-2.jpg" decoding="async" class="whcdn" width="460" height="345" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image_details"><script type="application/json">{"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/a4\/Tongue-Posture-Step-8-Version-2.jpg\/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-8-Version-2.jpg","bigUrl":"\/images\/thumb\/a\/a4\/Tongue-Posture-Step-8-Version-2.jpg\/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-8-Version-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":728,"bigHeight":546,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>\u00a9 2025 wikiHow, Inc. All rights reserved. wikiHow, Inc. is the copyright holder of this image under U.S. and international copyright laws. This image may not be used by other entities without the express written consent of wikiHow, Inc.<br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}</script></div></a></div>
<div class="step_num" aria-hidden="true">1</div><div class="step">
<b class="whb" aria-hidden="true">Tongue position awareness</b> Several times throughout the day, ask yourself where you feel your tongue, lips, and teeth when you’re at rest (like when you’re watching TV or driving). This will train you to check in with yourself more frequently and maintain your tongue position.<sup id="_ref-19" class="reference" aria-label="Link to Reference 19"><a href="#_note-19">[19]</a><span class="ts_popup " hidden id="ts_popup_19" style="display: none;">
	<span class="ts_close">X</span>
		<span class="ts_name">Research source</span>
		<span class="ts_description"></span>
				<a href="#" class="ts_source" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"></a>

</span>
</sup>
<ul><li>Also notice any times that you’re breathing through your mouth throughout the day. See if you can close your mouth and continue breathing easily. If not, you may need to see a dentist, ENT, or myofunctional specialist to fix potential issues with your airway.</li></ul>
</div>
<div class="clearall"></div>
<div class="scrolltomarker" data-isstep="1" id="scrollto_marker_steps_8"></div>
</li>
<li id="step-id-48">
<a name="step_5_2" class="stepanchor"></a><div class="mwimg  largeimage  floatcenter "><a href="#/Image:Tongue-Posture-Step-9-Version-2.jpg" class="image"><picture id="92c489518ac19831a6c1f191adc02d9a"><source type="image/webp" media="(max-width: 728px)" width="460" height="546" srcset="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/1b/Tongue-Posture-Step-9-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-9-Version-2.jpg.webp 460w"></source><source type="image/jpeg" media="(max-width: 728px)" width="460" height="546" srcset="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/1b/Tongue-Posture-Step-9-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-9-Version-2.jpg 460w"></source><source type="image/webp" media="(min-width: 729px)" width="728" height="546" srcset="/images/thumb/1/1b/Tongue-Posture-Step-9-Version-2.jpg/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-9-Version-2.jpg.webp 728w"></source><source type="image/jpeg" media="(min-width: 729px)" width="728" height="546" srcset="/images/thumb/1/1b/Tongue-Posture-Step-9-Version-2.jpg/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-9-Version-2.jpg 728w"></source><img alt="Step 2 Tongue retraction exercise" src="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/1b/Tongue-Posture-Step-9-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-9-Version-2.jpg" decoding="async" class="whcdn" width="460" height="345" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image_details"><script type="application/json">{"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/1\/1b\/Tongue-Posture-Step-9-Version-2.jpg\/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-9-Version-2.jpg","bigUrl":"\/images\/thumb\/1\/1b\/Tongue-Posture-Step-9-Version-2.jpg\/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-9-Version-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":728,"bigHeight":546,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>\u00a9 2025 wikiHow, Inc. All rights reserved. wikiHow, Inc. is the copyright holder of this image under U.S. and international copyright laws. This image may not be used by other entities without the express written consent of wikiHow, Inc.<br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}</script></div></a></div>
<div class="step_num" aria-hidden="true">2</div><div class="step">
<b class="whb" aria-hidden="true">Tongue retraction exercise</b> Sit up straight and slide your tongue backward so the tip is resting on the roof of your mouth behind your top teeth (it should not be touching your teeth). Slowly slide your tongue farther back toward your soft palate and hold the position for a few seconds before relaxing the tongue forward again. Repeat several times.<sup id="_ref-20" class="reference" aria-label="Link to Reference 20"><a href="#_note-20">[20]</a><span class="ts_popup " hidden id="ts_popup_20" style="display: none;">
	<span class="ts_close">X</span>
		<span class="ts_name">Research source</span>
		<span class="ts_description"></span>
				<a href="#" class="ts_source" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"></a>

</span>
</sup>
</div>
<div class="clearall"></div>
<div class="scrolltomarker" data-isstep="1" id="scrollto_marker_steps_9"></div>
</li>
<li id="step-id-49">
<a name="step_5_3" class="stepanchor"></a><div class="mwimg  largeimage  floatcenter "><a href="#/Image:Tongue-Posture-Step-10-Version-2.jpg" class="image"><picture id="10902d9938063a818f86c840393c77d8"><source type="image/webp" media="(max-width: 728px)" width="460" height="546" srcset="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a7/Tongue-Posture-Step-10-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-10-Version-2.jpg.webp 460w"></source><source type="image/jpeg" media="(max-width: 728px)" width="460" height="546" srcset="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a7/Tongue-Posture-Step-10-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-10-Version-2.jpg 460w"></source><source type="image/webp" media="(min-width: 729px)" width="728" height="546" srcset="/images/thumb/a/a7/Tongue-Posture-Step-10-Version-2.jpg/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-10-Version-2.jpg.webp 728w"></source><source type="image/jpeg" media="(min-width: 729px)" width="728" height="546" srcset="/images/thumb/a/a7/Tongue-Posture-Step-10-Version-2.jpg/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-10-Version-2.jpg 728w"></source><img alt="Step 3 Swallowing exercise" src="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a7/Tongue-Posture-Step-10-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-10-Version-2.jpg" decoding="async" class="whcdn" width="460" height="345" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image_details"><script type="application/json">{"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/a7\/Tongue-Posture-Step-10-Version-2.jpg\/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-10-Version-2.jpg","bigUrl":"\/images\/thumb\/a\/a7\/Tongue-Posture-Step-10-Version-2.jpg\/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-10-Version-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":728,"bigHeight":546,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>\u00a9 2025 wikiHow, Inc. All rights reserved. wikiHow, Inc. is the copyright holder of this image under U.S. and international copyright laws. This image may not be used by other entities without the express written consent of wikiHow, Inc.<br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}</script></div></a></div>
<div class="step_num" aria-hidden="true">3</div><div class="step">
<b class="whb" aria-hidden="true">Swallowing exercise</b> Sit up straight in a comfortable spot and place the tip of your tongue on the roof of your mouth behind your teeth. Then, gently swallow or make a sucking motion to force your tongue against the roof of your mouth via suction. Remember to keep the tip of your tongue firmly against your palate. Hold for a few seconds, and then release. Repeat several times a day.<sup id="_ref-21" class="reference" aria-label="Link to Reference 21"><a href="#_note-21">[21]</a><span class="ts_popup " hidden id="ts_popup_21" style="display: none;">
	<span class="ts_close">X</span>
		<span class="ts_name">Research source</span>
		<span class="ts_description"></span>
				<a href="#" class="ts_source" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"></a>

</span>
</sup>
</div>
<div class="clearall"></div>
<div class="scrolltomarker" data-isstep="1" id="scrollto_marker_steps_10"></div>
</li>
<li id="step-id-410">
<a name="step_5_4" class="stepanchor"></a><div class="mwimg  largeimage  floatcenter "><a href="#/Image:Tongue-Posture-Step-11-Version-2.jpg" class="image"><picture id="8cc8a222a8cb1a53d9e4fcb7cc354a9e"><source type="image/webp" media="(max-width: 728px)" width="460" height="546" srcset="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/4d/Tongue-Posture-Step-11-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-11-Version-2.jpg.webp 460w"></source><source type="image/jpeg" media="(max-width: 728px)" width="460" height="546" srcset="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/4d/Tongue-Posture-Step-11-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-11-Version-2.jpg 460w"></source><source type="image/webp" media="(min-width: 729px)" width="728" height="546" srcset="/images/thumb/4/4d/Tongue-Posture-Step-11-Version-2.jpg/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-11-Version-2.jpg.webp 728w"></source><source type="image/jpeg" media="(min-width: 729px)" width="728" height="546" srcset="/images/thumb/4/4d/Tongue-Posture-Step-11-Version-2.jpg/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-11-Version-2.jpg 728w"></source><img alt="Step 4 Tongue push-ups" src="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/4d/Tongue-Posture-Step-11-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-11-Version-2.jpg" decoding="async" class="whcdn" width="460" height="345" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image_details"><script type="application/json">{"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/4\/4d\/Tongue-Posture-Step-11-Version-2.jpg\/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-11-Version-2.jpg","bigUrl":"\/images\/thumb\/4\/4d\/Tongue-Posture-Step-11-Version-2.jpg\/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-11-Version-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":728,"bigHeight":546,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>\u00a9 2025 wikiHow, Inc. All rights reserved. wikiHow, Inc. is the copyright holder of this image under U.S. and international copyright laws. This image may not be used by other entities without the express written consent of wikiHow, Inc.<br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}</script></div></a></div>
<div class="step_num" aria-hidden="true">4</div><div class="step">
<b class="whb" aria-hidden="true">Tongue push-ups</b> Press the middle part of your tongue up against the roof of your mouth as hard as you can. Notice the tension in the muscles at the base of your tongue and in your throat and hold the position for several seconds. Relax the tongue, then repeat several times a day.<sup id="_ref-22" class="reference" aria-label="Link to Reference 22"><a href="#_note-22">[22]</a><span class="ts_popup " hidden id="ts_popup_22" style="display: none;">
	<span class="ts_close">X</span>
		<span class="ts_name">Research source</span>
		<span class="ts_description"></span>
				<a href="#" class="ts_source" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"></a>

</span>
</sup>
</div>
<div class="clearall"></div>
<div class="scrolltomarker" data-isstep="1" id="scrollto_marker_steps_11"></div>
</li>
<li id="step-id-411">
<a name="step_5_5" class="stepanchor"></a><div class="mwimg  largeimage  floatcenter "><a href="#/Image:Tongue-Posture-Step-12-Version-2.jpg" class="image"><picture id="a01ace3b30619092665347994d41465b"><source type="image/webp" media="(max-width: 728px)" width="460" height="546" srcset="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7c/Tongue-Posture-Step-12-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-12-Version-2.jpg.webp 460w"></source><source type="image/jpeg" media="(max-width: 728px)" width="460" height="546" srcset="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7c/Tongue-Posture-Step-12-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-12-Version-2.jpg 460w"></source><source type="image/webp" media="(min-width: 729px)" width="728" height="546" srcset="/images/thumb/7/7c/Tongue-Posture-Step-12-Version-2.jpg/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-12-Version-2.jpg.webp 728w"></source><source type="image/jpeg" media="(min-width: 729px)" width="728" height="546" srcset="/images/thumb/7/7c/Tongue-Posture-Step-12-Version-2.jpg/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-12-Version-2.jpg 728w"></source><img alt="Step 5 Speech therapy or orofacial myofunctional therapy" src="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7c/Tongue-Posture-Step-12-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-12-Version-2.jpg" decoding="async" class="whcdn" width="460" height="345" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image_details"><script type="application/json">{"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/7\/7c\/Tongue-Posture-Step-12-Version-2.jpg\/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-12-Version-2.jpg","bigUrl":"\/images\/thumb\/7\/7c\/Tongue-Posture-Step-12-Version-2.jpg\/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-12-Version-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":728,"bigHeight":546,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>\u00a9 2025 wikiHow, Inc. All rights reserved. wikiHow, Inc. is the copyright holder of this image under U.S. and international copyright laws. This image may not be used by other entities without the express written consent of wikiHow, Inc.<br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}</script></div></a></div>
<div class="step_num" aria-hidden="true">5</div><div class="step">
<b class="whb" aria-hidden="true">Speech therapy or orofacial myofunctional therapy</b> A speech-language pathologist (SLP) can work with you to strengthen and retrain your (or your child’s) tongue to rest properly. This kind of therapy usually involves specific exercises (like the ones above) for the tongue, lips, and cheeks.<sup id="_ref-23" class="reference trusted" aria-label="Link to Reference 23"><a href="#_note-23">[23]</a><span class="ts_popup trustedsource" hidden id="ts_popup_23" style="display: none;">
	<span class="ts_close">X</span>
		<a class="ts_trustworthy" href="/wikiHow:Delivering-a-Trustworthy-Experience">Trustworthy Source</a>

		<span class="ts_name">Cleveland Clinic</span>
		<span class="ts_description">Educational website from one of the world's leading hospitals</span>

				<a href="#" class="ts_source" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Go to source</a>
</span>
</sup>
<ul>
<li>Your primary care physician can recommend you to an SLP, or you may contact one directly. SLPs often work in schools, assisted living facilities and nursing homes, private practices or clinics, or rehabilitation centers.<sup id="_ref-24" class="reference trusted" aria-label="Link to Reference 24"><a href="#_note-24">[24]</a><span class="ts_popup trustedsource" hidden id="ts_popup_24" style="display: none;">
	<span class="ts_close">X</span>
		<a class="ts_trustworthy" href="/wikiHow:Delivering-a-Trustworthy-Experience">Trustworthy Source</a>

		<span class="ts_name">Cleveland Clinic</span>
		<span class="ts_description">Educational website from one of the world's leading hospitals</span>

				<a href="#" class="ts_source" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Go to source</a>
</span>
</sup>
</li>
<li>Anyone 4 years old and above is typically eligible for myofunctional therapy.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div class="clearall"></div>
<div class="scrolltomarker" data-isstep="1" id="scrollto_marker_steps_12"></div>
</li>
<li id="step-id-412">
<a name="step_5_6" class="stepanchor"></a><div class="mwimg  largeimage  floatcenter "><a href="#/Image:Tongue-Posture-Step-13-Version-2.jpg" class="image"><picture id="86145f081ee9caf111f4d4fce0127c25"><source type="image/webp" media="(max-width: 728px)" width="460" height="546" srcset="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/8a/Tongue-Posture-Step-13-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-13-Version-2.jpg.webp 460w"></source><source type="image/jpeg" media="(max-width: 728px)" width="460" height="546" srcset="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/8a/Tongue-Posture-Step-13-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-13-Version-2.jpg 460w"></source><source type="image/webp" media="(min-width: 729px)" width="728" height="546" srcset="/images/thumb/8/8a/Tongue-Posture-Step-13-Version-2.jpg/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-13-Version-2.jpg.webp 728w"></source><source type="image/jpeg" media="(min-width: 729px)" width="728" height="546" srcset="/images/thumb/8/8a/Tongue-Posture-Step-13-Version-2.jpg/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-13-Version-2.jpg 728w"></source><img alt="Step 6 Dental or orthodontic devices" src="https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/8a/Tongue-Posture-Step-13-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-13-Version-2.jpg" decoding="async" class="whcdn" width="460" height="345" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image_details"><script type="application/json">{"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/8\/8a\/Tongue-Posture-Step-13-Version-2.jpg\/v4-460px-Tongue-Posture-Step-13-Version-2.jpg","bigUrl":"\/images\/thumb\/8\/8a\/Tongue-Posture-Step-13-Version-2.jpg\/v4-728px-Tongue-Posture-Step-13-Version-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":728,"bigHeight":546,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>\u00a9 2025 wikiHow, Inc. All rights reserved. wikiHow, Inc. is the copyright holder of this image under U.S. and international copyright laws. This image may not be used by other entities without the express written consent of wikiHow, Inc.<br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}</script></div></a></div>
<div class="step_num" aria-hidden="true">6</div><div class="step">
<b class="whb" aria-hidden="true">Dental or orthodontic devices</b> A dentist or orthodontist may treat poor tongue posture (and the resulting side effects) with a variety of treatments. These may include a tongue crib to train the tongue’s movement (typically used for children with tongue thrust), braces, tooth aligners, or other devices.<sup id="_ref-25" class="reference trusted" aria-label="Link to Reference 25"><a href="#_note-25">[25]</a><span class="ts_popup trustedsource" hidden id="ts_popup_25" style="display: none;">
	<span class="ts_close">X</span>
		<a class="ts_trustworthy" href="/wikiHow:Delivering-a-Trustworthy-Experience">Trustworthy Source</a>

		<span class="ts_name">Cleveland Clinic</span>
		<span class="ts_description">Educational website from one of the world's leading hospitals</span>

				<a href="#" class="ts_source" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Go to source</a>
</span>
</sup>
<ul><li>Occasionally, a minor procedure or surgery may be needed to address severe bite problems or tongue abnormalities.</li></ul>
</div>
<div class="clearall"></div>
<div class="scrolltomarker" data-isstep="1" id="scrollto_marker_steps_13"></div>
</li>
<div class="wh_ad_inner w_label al_grey dfpsmall dfpsmallmethod containerless_ad fluid" data-service="adsense" data-slot="7710650179" data-width="728" data-height="90" data-smallheight="250" data-type="method" data-small="1" data-channels="4657739586" data-smallservice="dfp" data-adunitpath="/10095428/engl/engl_gam_sma_meth0" data-size='[[300, 250],"fluid"]' data-apsload="1" data-prebidload="1" data-aps-timeout="800" data-containerless="1" data-fullwidthadsense="1" data-fluidsize="1" data-mediumchannels="3005955957,4066873649" data-smallchannels="2811805837,8156154280" data-aditudetarget="pb-slot-engl-meth" data-largechannels="2060152247,5763098696" data-insertslotvalue="4" data-pagetype="methods" data-observerloading="1" data-sizes-array='[[300, 250],"fluid"]' data-gptdisplaylate="1" data-pbadunits='{"appnexus":29111279,"pubmatic":"4926794","ix":"944751","amx":"d2lraWhvdy5jb20","rubicon":"2756126","shemedia":"2952570","openx":"558892622","triplelift":"Wikihow_engl_gam_sma_meth0_300x250_Prebid","yieldmo":"3204666393567896410","grid":383057,"medianet":"521047606","rise":"engl_gam_sma_meth0","sharethrough":"xZq2HSiUJL1GRBHUi49ybeLd"}'><div id="mobilemethod_ad_5"></div></div>
